This recipe is incredibly simple, quick and delicious. Ive made this with baked, grilled, seared fish, but our favorite is fried. I sprinkle the filet with flour, then dredge in a little egg-wash, then coat it in panko and give it a quick fry. I place a pat or two of butter on the filets and place them in the oven to keep warm. The fish comes out golden, crunchy, perfect&.

Rating: 4
First off this is a good recipe! I tried it once according to this site but then I had to put my spin on it. I found that after following the original recipe it lacked salt, fire & tang. How did I fix that? First off in a bowl, add 1 tablespoon of salt (yes one tablespoon). Next I added double the lime zest and a half; I chopped 1 jalapeno and added a tablespoon & a half of dried red chili pepper. Believe me: it balances out because of the butter. To maximize on flavor, add the salt to a bowl first, followed by the zest, shallot & peppers then the juice. Allow to marinate for a minute. Once I did that, I incorporated everything and wrapped and refrigerated it. To serve: I placed a disk (or 2) of the treated butter on top the fish and I zapped it in the microwave for 30 seconds to help the melting along. IT WAS DIVINITY! Try it! Serve over mashed potatoes and steamed green beans! YUMMY! Oh and by the way to make a nice crust dust the fish with some flour. I used cod -- It was superior to the tilapia.

